author: Al Jazeera English
description:
Speaking at this year's COP30 in Brazil, UN chief Antonio Guterres called the inability to limit global warming to 1.5 degrees Celsius a "deadly moral failure".
But does the same apply when it comes protecting the environment in conflict?

Israel's two-year genocide on Gaza has created 61 million tons of rubble, with nearly a quarter contaminated with asbestos and other hazardous materials. 
And scientists warn Israel's use of water, food, and energy as weapons of war in the strip has left farmland and ecosystems facing irreversible collapse.

In Syria, President Ahmed al-Sharaa has cited his country’s worst drought in more than six decades as evidence of accelerating climate change, and warned it could hinder the country's post-war recovery.

So why isn’t conflict seen as a climate issue and why is the environmental toll of war so often ignored?

Presenter: Adrian Finighan

Guests: 

Kate Mackintosh - Deputy Chair of Independent Expert Panel for the legal definition of Ecocide

Elain
title: Is war one of the biggest threats to the world’s climate? | Inside Story

author: Al Jazeera English
description:
Doctors in Sudan say the paramilitary Rapid Support Forces has been concealing evidence of its atrocities.
The Sudan Doctors Network says fighters have been burning or burying bodies in mass graves in an attempt to cover up killings in the Darfur region.
The RSF took over el-Fasher, the capital of North Darfur, two weeks ago, after driving out the army.
The UN says there are reports of brutal attacks as people tried to flee the city. 

Al Jazeera’s Hiba Morgan has more from Khartoum, Sudan.

The RSF takeover of el-Fasher is a significant development in the conflict because it means the paramilitary group now controls most of the Darfur region.
The UN estimates 82,000 people fled el-Fasher when fighters seized the city.
Most of them were women and children. They fled on foot to the town of Tawila, around 60 kilometres away.
Some survivors travelled for many days, covering hundreds of kilometres, to reach a displacement camp in Al Dabbah in Northern State.

Waseem Solangi is the Sudan C
title: Sudan medics accuse RSF of burning, burying bodies to conceal ‘genocide’

author: Al Jazeera English
description:
The director-general of the British Broadcasting Corporation (BBC) has resigned after a row over the editing of a speech made by US President Donald Trump on the day of the 2021 attack on the United States Capitol.

Sunday’s joint resignations of Tim Davie and head of news Deborah Turness capped a turbulent week of accusations that the broadcaster edited a speech Trump made on January 6, 2021, to make it appear as if he encouraged the riots that followed his defeat in the 2020 presidential election.

Al Jazeera’s Rory Challands reports from London.

author: Al Jazeera English
description:
The US Senate is holding a vote that could pave the way to end the longest government shutdown in American history. Senators are voting on a Republican stopgap funding package. The package would reopen the government into January and fund some parts of the government for the next year. The Republicans need Democrat support for that to happen. Healthcare funding has been a major sticking point.

Al Jazeera’s Mike Hanna joins live from Washington, DC, while Niall Stanage, a political analyst and the White House columnist for The Hill, joins live from Washington, DC.
